The science commons might have useful material:

http://sciencecommons.org/

The adelphi charter may be of interest:

http://www.adelphicharter.org/adelphi_charter.asp

As may openbusiness and icommons:

http://www.openbusiness.cc/

http://www.icommons.org/

Quoting Björn Lindström <bkhl@stp.lingfil.uu.se>:

> Dessi Pefeva <dpefeva@isoc.bg>:
>
>> I missed the word "full" before copyright.
>
> The Creative Commons licenses uses the regular old copyright. There's
> nothing "less copyrighted" about it compared to "all rights reserved"
> distribution.

CC can be viewed as providing an alternative to "all rights reserved".  
Since ARR is the full set of rights given by copyright, CC can  
usefully (and logically) be regarded as being different from full  
copyright, however it effects this legally.

I appreciate that it's important to get this right from a legal point of view.

- Rob.

